article.headline: Perkins leads Texas Tech to easy victory
article.linkText: Early run helps Texas Tech put away Iowa State
article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Texas Tech had a simple game plan against
Iowa State: patience on offense and persistence on defense.

	   It worked Sunday, as the (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) Lady Raiders beat Iowa State 70-48.

	   "On the offensive end, that's as closely as we've followed our
plan this year,'' Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp said. "Because we
were able to do that, it made the day much easier.''

	   The Lady Raiders (19-2, 8-1) got 19 points from Jia Perkins and
12 from Miklannet Tennal in defeating Iowa State (9-11, 4-5).

	   "Texas Tech is an outstanding team,'' Iowa State coach Bill
Fennelly said. "They are as good as any team we've played this
year, and we've played Kansas State and Duke. They have
star-quality players in (Plenette) Pierson and Perkins, and they
are a great defensive team with great depth.''

	   The Lady Raiders took control midway through the first half,
running off 15 unanswered points to open a 29-8 cushion with 4:44 remaining.

	   Tennal hit two 3-pointers during the flurry, and Pierson added a
basket and a free throw.

	   Jolee Ayers made a baseline jumper and Casey Jackson hit a
12-footer before Perkins capped the run with a spectacular running
layup.

	   "That's something I've been practicing on,'' Perkins joked
after the game. "I was just trying to push the ball. I was running
fast, saw a little lane, I thought, and tried to scoop it under
them. I would never think of actually doing that. It just
happened.''

	   "They were guarding Natalie (Ritchie) pretty hard,'' Tennal
added. "They left me open a couple of times in the first half.
It's easy to make shots when no one's guarding you.''

	   Iowa State got no closer than 33-17 the rest of the first half,
and Tech held a 34-17 lead at halftime.

	   After falling behind by as many as 20 points in the first half,
the Cyclones made a push to get back in the game early in the
second half.

	   Lisa Kriener sandwiched two baskets around a driving layup by
Lindsey Wilson as Iowa State pulled to 36-23 with 16:56 remaining.
But the Lady Raiders answered with consecutive baskets from Ritchie
and Ayers.

	   A 15-footer by Perkins later in the half stretched the lead to
53-33 with 9:48 remaining. Iowa State got no closer than 17 points
the rest of the way.

	   Pierson finished with 12 points for Tech.

	   Iowa State was led by Wilson, who had 17 points. Kriener added
10.

	   "I like the way they play,'' Fennelly said. "I like their
approach to the game, and I have great respect for Marsha Sharp and
her staff. Someone would have to play their brains out to beat them
in this building.''
